Phenomena related to electric charge

For other uses, see [Electricity (disambiguation)](/Electricity_(disambiguation)). "Electric" redirects here. For other uses, see [Electric (disambiguation)](/Electric_(disambiguation)).

Electricity is an invisible force, yet its presence is undeniably manifest in the spectacular flash of [lightning](/Lightning) and the steady glow of [electric light](/Electric_light) illuminating our cities. These are but visual whispers of a phenomenon that underpins so much of our existence. It is a fundamental aspect of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism), inextricably linked with [magnetism](/Magnetism), [optics](/Optics), and a rich tapestry of [computational](/Computational_electromagnetics) theories and historical inquiries.

At its core, electricity is about [electric charge](/Electric_charge). The presence of this charge, whether positive or negative, sculpts the space around it into an [electric field](/Electric_field). When these charges, these fundamental carriers of electrical essence, begin to move, they form an [electric current](/Electric_current). This motion, this flow, is governed by the immutable laws of physics, with [Coulomb's law](/Coulomb's_law) dictating the forces at play between charged [particles](/Particle_(physics)). The energy required to coax a charge from one point to another within this field, a measure of its potential, is quantified as [electric potential](/Electric_potential), typically expressed in the humble yet powerful [volts](/Volt).

The practical applications of electricity are so pervasive they are almost invisible, like the air we breathe. It powers our world through [electric power](/Electric_power), energizing everything from the smallest gadget to the largest industrial complex. And in the realm of [electronics](/Electronics), it's the very lifeblood, flowing through intricate [electrical circuits](/Electrical_circuits) populated by [active components](/Active_device) like [vacuum tubes](/Vacuum_tube), [transistors](/Transistor), and [integrated circuits](/Integrated_circuit), all interconnected by a web of passive technologies.

The journey to understanding electricity was a long, winding road, stretching back to antiquity. Even then, whispers of its power were known, felt in the shocking embrace of [electric fish](/Electric_fish). Ancient Egyptians, as far back as [2750 BCE](/28th_century_BC), spoke of these creatures as "protectors." Millennia later, [ancient Greek](/Ancient_Greek), [Roman](/Roman_Empire), and [Arab naturalists](/Science_in_the_medieval_Islamic_world) and [physicians](/Islamic_medicine) documented these uncanny encounters, noting the numbing effect of [electric shocks](/Electric_shock) from [electric catfish](/Electric_catfish) and [electric rays](/Electric_ray). They even observed that these shocks could traverse conducting materials, leading to crude early attempts at medical treatment for ailments like [gout](/Gout) and [headache](/Headache) by harnessing the fish's potent jolt.

The curiosity about static phenomena, the gentle attraction of light objects to rubbed amber, was noted by [Thales of Miletus](/Thales_of_Miletus) around 600 BCE. He posited that friction endowed amber with a [magnetic](/Magnetic) quality, a notion that, while incorrect, hinted at the complex relationship between electrical and magnetic forces that would later be unveiled. A more enigmatic clue emerged with the discovery of the [Baghdad Battery](/Baghdad_Battery), a relic resembling a [galvanic cell](/Galvanic_cell), suggesting a potential, albeit unconfirmed, understanding of electrochemistry by the ancient [Parthians](/Parthia).

For centuries, electricity remained a philosophical curiosity, a scientific enigma. It wasn't until the dawn of the 17th century that a more systematic inquiry began. [William Gilbert](/William_Gilbert_(astronomer)), in his seminal 1600 work, [De&#160;Magnete](/De_Magnete), meticulously distinguished between the magnetic properties of lodestone and the static electricity generated by rubbing amber. He coined the term "electricus," derived from the Greek "elektron" for amber, giving rise to the English words "electric" and "electricity" which first graced the pages of [Thomas Browne](/Thomas_Browne)'s [Pseudodoxia Epidemica](/Pseudodoxia_Epidemica) in 1646. Even [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton) touched upon these forces in his [Opticks](/Opticks), his musings arguably foreshadowing the concept of [field theory](/Field_(physics)) in describing electric forces.

The 17th and early 18th centuries saw a flurry of investigations by figures like [Otto von Guericke](/Otto_von_Guericke), [Robert Boyle](/Robert_Boyle), and [Stephen Gray](/Stephen_Gray_(scientist)). Then came [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin), a polymath whose relentless pursuit of electrical knowledge, funded by the sale of his possessions, led to groundbreaking discoveries. His legendary [kite experiment](/Kite_experiment) in June 1752, though perhaps embellished in popular retelling, famously demonstrated that lightning was indeed an electrical phenomenon. Franklin also offered a crucial insight into the nature of charge, proposing it existed in two forms, positive and negative, and explaining the storage capacity of the [Leyden jar](/Leyden_jar).

The 19th century ushered in an era of profound understanding and application. [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday)'s pivotal discoveries laid the groundwork for the electric motor, transforming theoretical concepts into tangible devices. The work of [Luigi Galvani](/Luigi_Galvani) on [bioelectromagnetics](/Bioelectromagnetics) revealed the electrical nature of nerve signals, while [Alessandro Volta](/Alessandro_Volta)'s 1800 invention of the [voltaic pile](/Voltaic_pile) provided a consistent and reliable source of electrical energy, surpassing the limitations of earlier [electrostatic machines](/Electrostatic_machine). The true unification of electricity and magnetism, the concept of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism), was cemented by the observations of [Hans Christian Ørsted](/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted) and the subsequent theoretical work of [André-Marie Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re). By 1827, [Georg Ohm](/Georg_Ohm) had provided the mathematical framework for analyzing electrical circuits. The culmination of this understanding arrived with [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell)'s groundbreaking equations in the 1860s, which unified electricity, magnetism, and light into a single, elegant theory.

The latter half of the 19th century witnessed an explosion in [electrical engineering](/Electrical_engineering), driven by innovators like [Thomas Edison](/Thomas_Edison), [Nikola Tesla](/Nikola_Tesla), and [George Westinghouse](/George_Westinghouse). Electricity transitioned from a laboratory marvel to the indispensable engine of the [Second Industrial Revolution](/Second_Industrial_Revolution), reshaping industry and society. In 1905, [Albert Einstein](/Albert_Einstein)'s explanation of the [photoelectric effect](/Photoelectric_effect) opened the door to the quantum revolution, earning him the [Nobel Prize in Physics](/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics) and paving the way for technologies like [solar panels](/Solar_panel). The invention of the [transistor](/Transistor) at [Bell Labs](/Bell_Labs) in 1947 marked the birth of [solid-state electronics](/Solid-state_electronics), revolutionizing computing and communication.

Concepts

Electric charge

•
Main article: [Electric charge](/Electric_charge)

•
See also: [Electron](/Electron), [Proton](/Proton), and [Ion](/Ion)

The visible repulsion of leaves on a [gold-leaf electroscope](/Gold-leaf_electroscope) is a tangible demonstration of [electric charge](/Electric_charge). By convention, the charge carried by [electrons](/Electron) is designated as negative, and that of [protons](/Proton) as positive. This convention traces back to [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin), who defined the charge on glass rubbed with silk as positive. The fundamental unit of charge is the [elementary charge](/Elementary_charge), a value of 1.602176634×10⁻¹⁹ [coulombs](/Coulomb). No smaller unit of charge exists, and any charge is a multiple of this fundamental value. Electrons carry an equal and opposite negative charge. Charge isn't confined to ordinary matter; [antimatter](/Antimatter) possesses an equal and opposite charge to its matter counterpart.

The interaction between charges manifests as an electrostatic force, a phenomenon recognized since antiquity. This force, governed by [Coulomb's law](/Coulomb's_law), is incredibly powerful, second only to the [strong interaction](/Strong_interaction), yet it operates across all distances. While gravity is a universally attractive force, the electrostatic force can be either attractive or repulsive, a duality that explains why gravity dominates on cosmic scales where matter is often electrically neutral. The magnitude of this force diminishes with the square of the distance separating the charges.

Charge is an intrinsic property of certain [subatomic particles](/Subatomic_particle), primarily the [electron](/Electron) and [proton](/Proton). It interacts with the [electromagnetic force](/Electromagnetic_force), one of nature's four [fundamental forces](/Fundamental_force). Crucially, electric charge is a [conserved quantity](/Conserved_quantity); the total charge in an isolated system remains constant, though it can be transferred between objects through contact or conductive materials. The term [static electricity](/Static_electricity) describes an imbalance of charge, often created by friction between dissimilar materials. Early instruments like the [gold-leaf electroscope](/Gold-leaf_electroscope), and later the [electrometer](/Electrometer), were developed to measure these elusive charges.

Electric current

•
Main article: [Electric current](/Electric_current)

The relentless flow of electric charge is what we call [electric current](/Electric_current), measured in [amperes](/Ampere). This current can be a movement of any charged particles, but most commonly it's the drift of electrons. Some materials, [electrical conductors](/Electrical_conductor), readily permit this flow, while others, [electrical insulators](/Electrical_insulator), resist it.

Historically, the direction of current was defined by the flow of positive charge, from a region of higher potential to lower potential. This is known as [conventional current](/Conventional_current). The actual movement of electrons, which are negatively charged, is in the opposite direction. However, the convention remains, simplifying circuit analysis. Electric currents can be surprisingly complex, involving movement in one direction, the opposite, or even simultaneous bidirectional flow.

The physical process of current flow is [electrical conduction](/Electrical_conduction), and its nature depends on the charge carriers and the medium. In metals, it's the electron's dance through the atomic lattice. In liquids, it's the migration of [ions](/Ion) during [electrolysis](/Electrolysis). Even in [plasmas](/Plasma_(physics)), like those found in electrical sparks, charged particles carry the current. While individual charge carriers might move at a leisurely pace – a mere fraction of a millimeter per second in some cases – the driving [electric field](/Electric_field) propagates at near the [speed of light](/Speed_of_light), allowing electrical signals to traverse wires with astonishing rapidity.

The effects of electric current are observable and historically significant. The decomposition of water by current, observed by [Nicholson](/William_Nicholson_(chemist)) and [Carlisle](/Anthony_Carlisle) in 1800, led to the understanding of [electrolysis](/Electrolysis). The heating effect, known as [Joule heating](/Joule_heating), where current dissipates energy as heat in a [resistance](/Electrical_resistance), was meticulously studied by [James Prescott Joule](/James_Prescott_Joule). Perhaps the most profound discovery was [Hans Christian Ørsted](/Hans_Christian_%C3%98rsted)'s accidental observation in 1820: a current-carrying wire could deflect a magnetic compass needle. This revealed the intrinsic link between electricity and magnetism, the phenomenon of [electromagnetism](/Electromagnetism). The intense electromagnetic emissions from [electric arcs](/Electric_arc) can cause [electromagnetic interference](/Electromagnetic_interference), a critical consideration in sensitive electronic systems.

In practical terms, currents are classified as either [direct current](/Direct_current) (DC) or [alternating current](/Alternating_current) (AC). DC, typically supplied by a [battery](/Battery_(electricity)), flows unidirectionally, essential for most [electronic](/Electronics) devices. AC, the standard for power distribution, periodically reverses direction, often in a [sine wave](/Sine_wave) pattern. While AC's net charge displacement is zero over a cycle, it efficiently delivers energy. AC's behavior is influenced by properties like [inductance](/Inductance) and [capacitance](/Capacitance), which become significant during transitional states.

Electric field

•
Main article: [Electric field](/Electric_field)

•
See also: [Electrostatics](/Electrostatics)

The concept of the electric [field](/Field_(physics)) owes much to [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday). It's the invisible influence a charged object exerts on the space around it, capable of imparting a force on any other charge that enters its domain. Akin to the gravitational field generated by [masses](/Mass), the electric field extends infinitely and follows an inverse-square relationship with distance. However, unlike gravity, which is always attractive, the electric field can be either attractive or repulsive, depending on the nature of the charges involved. This distinction is why gravity is the dominant force at cosmic scales, where matter tends to be electrically neutral.

Field lines, conceptual representations of the electric field, emanate from positive charges and terminate on negative ones. These lines, a visualization tool introduced by Faraday, depict the path a hypothetical positive charge would follow. They are a useful construct for understanding field behavior but have no physical existence themselves. Key principles govern these lines: they originate on positive charges and end on negative ones, they meet conductors at right angles, and they never cross each other.

A remarkable property of conductors is that any net charge resides entirely on their outer surface. Consequently, the electric field inside a hollow conductor is zero, a principle utilized in the [Faraday cage](/Faraday_cage) to shield sensitive equipment from external electrical effects.

Understanding electric fields is paramount in designing high-voltage equipment. Every medium has a limit to the electric field strength it can withstand before [electrical breakdown](/Electrical_breakdown) occurs, often resulting in an [electric arc](/Electric_arc). For air, this breakdown typically happens at around 30 kV per centimeter, though this value can be lower over larger distances. The most dramatic natural manifestation of this phenomenon is [lightning](/Lightning), a colossal discharge resulting from charge separation within clouds, creating electric fields that far exceed the air's dielectric strength. A lightning strike can carry immense voltage and energy.

The presence of nearby conductors significantly alters electric field strength, and sharp points can concentrate the field intensely. This principle is leveraged in [lightning conductors](/Lightning_conductor), designed to provide a preferential path for lightning strikes, protecting structures.

Electric potential

•
Main article: [Electric potential](/Electric_potential)

•
See also: [Voltage](/Voltage) and [Electric battery](/Electric_battery)

The positive and negative terminals of [AA cells](/AA_cell) signify a [potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference), a fundamental concept linked to the electric field. Electric potential at a point is defined as the [work](/Work_(physics)) required to bring a unit positive test charge from an infinite distance to that point, without acceleration. This energy is measured in [volts](/Volt), where one volt represents the potential requiring one [joule](/Joule) of work for a charge of one [coulomb](/Coulomb). While this definition is formal, the more practical concept is [electric potential difference](/Electric_potential_difference), the energy needed to move a unit charge between two specific points. Since the electric field is [conservative](/Conservative_force), the path taken is irrelevant; the potential difference is unique. The term [voltage](/Voltage) is commonly used interchangeably with electric potential difference.

For practical reference, the [Earth](/Earth) is often designated as having zero potential, providing a universal benchmark. This concept of an [earth](/Ground_(electricity)) or [ground](/Ground_(electricity)) connection is vital in electrical systems.

Electric potential is a [scalar quantity](/Scalar_(physics)), possessing only magnitude. It can be analogized to height in a gravitational field: just as an object falls from a higher to a lower height, a positive charge will move from a region of higher electric potential to one of lower potential. Lines of equal potential, known as [equipotentials](/Equipotential), can be mapped, and they intersect electric field lines at right angles. Within a conductor, equipotentials must be parallel to the surface, ensuring no net force moves charges along it in a static situation.

The electric field can also be defined as the [gradient](/Gradient) of the electric potential, typically expressed in volts per meter. The field's direction points towards the steepest descent of potential, where equipotentials are closest together.

Electromagnets

•
Main article: [Electromagnets](/Electromagnets)

The delicate dance of magnetic field lines encircling a current-carrying wire, a visualization of the forces at play.

Ørsted's 1821 discovery that an electric current generates a [magnetic field](/Magnetic_field) marked a watershed moment, revealing a profound connection between electricity and magnetism. This interaction was distinct from gravity and electrostatics; the force on a compass needle wasn't directed towards or away from the wire, but rather at a right angle, a "revolving manner" as described by Ørsted. The direction of the current dictated the direction of the force, a reciprocity that [Ampère](/Andr%C3%A9-Marie_Amp%C3%A8re) would further explore, establishing the fundamental laws governing the interaction between parallel currents.

This magnetic force exerted by currents became the cornerstone of [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday)'s invention of the [electric motor](/Electric_motor) in 1821. His ingenious [homopolar motor](/Homopolar_motor) utilized the tangential force on a current-carrying wire within a magnetic field to create continuous rotation.

Faraday's equally significant discovery in 1831, [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction), demonstrated that a changing magnetic field could induce a potential difference in a conductor. This principle, encapsulated in [Faraday's law of induction](/Faraday%27s_law_of_induction), led to the invention of the first [electrical generator](/Electrical_generator). While his experimental [Faraday's disc](/Faraday%27s_disc) was inefficient, it proved the concept of generating electricity from mechanical motion and magnetism, a principle that would fuel future innovations.

Electric circuits

•
Main article: [Electric circuit](/Electric_circuit)

A fundamental [electric circuit](/Electric_circuit): a [voltage source](/Voltage_source) (V) drives a [current](/Current_(electricity)) (I) through a [resistor](/Resistor) (R), completing the path back to the source. This closed loop allows for the controlled flow of electrical energy.

An electric circuit is an intricate network of interconnected components designed to channel the flow of electric charge along a closed path, typically to accomplish a specific task. These circuits can range from the simplest arrangements to highly complex systems.

The components within an electric circuit can be broadly categorized as [passive](/Passivity_(engineering)) or [active](/Active_device). Passive components, such as [resistors](/Resistor), [capacitors](/Capacitor), and [inductors](/Inductor), do not generate energy but can store or dissipate it. Active components, found in [electronic circuits](/Electronic_circuit), like [transistors](/Transistor) and [diodes](/Diode), can amplify or control electrical signals, exhibiting [non-linear](/Non-linear_element) behavior.

The [resistor](/Resistor) is a fundamental passive element that impedes the flow of current, converting electrical energy into heat. Its behavior is described by [Ohm's law](/Ohm%27s_law), which states that the current through a resistor is directly proportional to the voltage across it. The unit of resistance is the [ohm](/Ohm), named in honor of [Georg Ohm](/Georg_Ohm).

The [capacitor](/Capacitor), an evolution of the [Leyden jar](/Leyden_jar), stores electrical energy in an electric field. It consists of two conductive plates separated by an insulating [dielectric](/Dielectric). When connected to a voltage source, it initially draws current as it accumulates charge, but this current decays over time, ultimately blocking steady-state flow. The unit of capacitance is the [farad](/Farad), named after [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday).

The [inductor](/Inductor), typically a coil of wire, stores energy in a magnetic field generated by the current flowing through it. Changes in current induce a voltage across the inductor, a property described by its [inductance](/Inductance). The unit of inductance is the [henry](/Henry_(unit)), named after [Joseph Henry](/Joseph_Henry). Inductors resist changes in current, behaving in a manner somewhat opposite to capacitors.

Electric power

•
Main article: [electric power](/Electric_power)

[Electric power](/Electric_power) is the rate at which [electric energy](/Electric_energy) is transferred within an [electric circuit](/Electric_circuit). The standard unit for power is the [watt](/Watt_(unit)), equivalent to one [joule](/Joule) per [second](/Second).

Power, whether electrical or mechanical, represents the rate of doing [work](/Work_(physics)). For electricity, it's calculated as the product of current (I) and voltage (V): P = IV. This equation underscores the fundamental relationship between these three quantities.

Electricity is delivered to consumers by the [electric power industry](/Electric_power_industry), typically measured and billed by the [kilowatt hour](/Kilowatt_hour), a unit representing the energy consumed by a 1-kilowatt device operating for one hour. Electricity meters track this consumption. Unlike many forms of energy, electricity is a low-[entropy](/Entropy) form, meaning it can be converted into other forms of energy, such as motion, with high efficiency.

Electronics

•
Main article: [electronics](/Electronics)

The intricate world of [electronics](/Electronics) revolves around [electrical circuits](/Electrical_circuit) that employ [active components](/Active_device) like [transistors](/Transistor), [diodes](/Diode), and [integrated circuits](/Integrated_circuit). These components, often based on [semiconductor](/Semiconductor) materials, exhibit [nonlinear](/Nonlinear_element) behavior, enabling complex functions such as digital switching and information processing. The principles governing semiconductors are explored in [solid state physics](/Solid_state_physics), while the practical design and application of electronic circuits fall under [electronics engineering](/Electronics_engineering).

The [transistor](/Transistor), a monumental invention of the 20th century, is a foundational element of modern electronics. Today's [integrated circuits](/Integrated_circuit) can house billions of these miniaturized transistors within a tiny space, driving the advancements in computing and communication that define our era.

Electromagnetic wave

•
Main article: [Electromagnetic wave](/Electromagnetic_wave)

The interplay between time-varying electric and magnetic fields gives rise to [electromagnetic waves](/Electromagnetic_wave). [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell) in 1864 formulated a set of equations that elegantly described this relationship, demonstrating that these waves propagate at the [speed of light](/Speed_of_light). This revelation unified the understanding of light, electric fields, and magnetic fields into a single, coherent theory, a monumental achievement in physics. The ability to generate and detect these waves has revolutionized [telecommunications](/Telecommunications), allowing for the transmission of information across vast distances via radio waves.

Production, storage and uses

Generation and transmission

•
Main article: [Electricity generation](/Electricity_generation)

•
See also: [Electric power transmission](/Electric_power_transmission) and [Mains electricity](/Mains_electricity)

The early experiments with amber rods by [Thales of Miletus](/Thales_of_Miletus), while rudimentary, marked the first explorations into electricity production. However, it was the invention of the [voltaic pile](/Voltaic_pile) by [Alessandro Volta](/Alessandro_Volta) that provided a practical source of electrical energy, paving the way for the development of [electrical batteries](/Battery_(electricity)) that store energy chemically.

The vast majority of electrical power today is generated by electro-mechanical [generators](/Electrical_generator). These are often driven by steam produced from [fossil fuel](/Fossil_fuel) combustion or nuclear reactions, but also by the kinetic energy of wind or water. The [steam turbine](/Steam_turbine), perfected by [Sir Charles Parsons](/Charles_Algernon_Parsons), remains a key technology for converting thermal energy into rotational motion for generators. Modern generators, while vastly more sophisticated, still operate on the fundamental principle of [electromagnetic induction](/Electromagnetic_induction) discovered by [Michael Faraday](/Michael_Faraday). An alternative, [solar panels](/Solar_panel), directly convert [solar radiation](/Solar_irradiance) into electricity via the [photovoltaic effect](/Photovoltaic_effect).

The demand for electricity escalates with economic development and modernization. Emerging economies are currently experiencing growth rates seen in the early 20th century United States. Growing concerns about the environmental impact of [fossil fuel](/Fossil_fuel) combustion, particularly its contribution to [climate change](/Climate_change), are driving a significant shift towards [renewable energy](/Renewable_energy) sources like [wind](/Wind_power) and [solar](/Solar_PV), accelerating an [energy transition](/Energy_transition).

Transmission and storage

The invention of the [transformer](/Transformer) in the late 19th century revolutionized electricity transmission, enabling power to be sent efficiently at high voltages and low currents. This allowed for centralized [power stations](/Power_station) to supply electricity over long distances, benefiting from [economies of scale](/Economies_of_scale).

A significant challenge in electricity systems is storage. Unlike many other forms of energy, electricity is difficult to store in large quantities, meaning supply must precisely match demand. Maintaining [reserve](/Operating_reserve) capacity is crucial to ensure grid stability. The increasing integration of variable renewable sources like wind and solar has amplified the need for effective energy storage solutions. Technologies such as [batteries](/Electric_battery), chemical storage (like [hydrogen](/Hydrogen)), and thermal or mechanical storage are being developed and deployed to bridge the gap between supply and demand.

Applications

The practical application of electricity is vast and ever-expanding. The invention of the [incandescent light bulb](/Incandescent_light_bulb) in the 1870s transformed [lighting](/Lighting), offering a safer and more efficient alternative to gas lamps and significantly reducing fire hazards in homes and factories. This led to the establishment of public utilities and the widespread electrification of urban areas. In recent decades, the sector has seen deregulation, altering how electricity is supplied and managed.

[Joule heating](/Joule_heating), the principle behind filament light bulbs, is also directly applied in [electric heating](/Electric_heating). While convenient, it's often seen as inefficient, as generating electricity typically involves producing heat at the power source. Some countries have implemented regulations to limit or ban resistive electric heating in new construction. Nevertheless, electricity remains a vital energy source for heating and [refrigeration](/Refrigeration), with [air conditioning](/Air_conditioning) and [heat pumps](/Heat_pump) representing a growing demand sector. Electrification is poised to play a crucial role in the [decarbonisation](/Decarbonisation) of sectors like transport ([electric vehicles](/Electric_vehicles)) and heating ([heat pumps](/Heat_pumps)).

The [electric motor](/Electric_motor), a prime example of applied electromagnetism, provides a clean and efficient means of motive power. Motors are used in a myriad of applications, from stationary equipment like winches to mobile systems such as [electric vehicles](/Electric_vehicle), which either carry onboard power sources like batteries or collect current from external infrastructure. Electric trains, buses, and cars are increasingly becoming commonplace.

Electricity is also the backbone of modern [telecommunications](/Telecommunications), enabling everything from the historical [electrical telegraphs](/Electrical_telegraph) that spanned continents to today's instantaneous global communication networks.

Electricity and the natural world

Physiological effects

•
Main article: [Electrical injury](/Electrical_injury)

When electricity flows through the human body, it generates a current through tissues. The magnitude of this current is generally proportional to the applied voltage, though the relationship is non-linear. Even a small current, as low as a microampere under certain conditions, can be perceived as [electrovibration](/Electrovibration). Higher currents can cause muscle contractions, cardiac [fibrillation](/Fibrillation), and severe tissue [burns](/Burn). The invisible nature of electricity makes it a particularly insidious hazard. The intense pain of an electric shock has historically led to its use as a form of [torture](/Torture). In some parts of the world, [electrocution](/Electrocution) remains a method of [capital punishment](/Capital_punishment), though its use has declined significantly.

Electrical phenomena in nature

•
Main article: [Electrical phenomena](/Electrical_phenomena)

Electricity is not solely a human construct; it is a pervasive force in nature. [Lightning](/Lightning) is its most dramatic manifestation. Many everyday interactions, from [touch](/Touch) to [chemical bonding](/Chemical_bond), are fundamentally driven by electric fields at the atomic level. The Earth's own [magnetic field](/Earth%27s_magnetic_field) is generated by the dynamic interplay of currents within its core, a natural [dynamo](/Dynamo_theory). Certain crystals, like [quartz](/Quartz), exhibit [piezoelectricity](/Piezoelectricity)—generating a voltage when subjected to mechanical pressure—a phenomenon discovered by the Curie brothers. This effect is reversible; applying an electric field causes the crystal to deform.

Remarkably, some organisms have evolved the ability to sense or generate electricity. [Sharks](/Shark) possess [electroreception](/Electroreception) to detect the weak electric fields of prey, while [electric fish](/Electric_fish), such as the [electric eel](/Electric_eel), generate powerful voltages to stun predators or capture prey using specialized cells called [electrocytes](/Electrocytes). Even within our own bodies, [action potentials](/Action_potential)—voltage pulses across cell membranes—are the fundamental mechanism for nerve signaling between [neurons](/Neuron) and [muscles](/Muscle), coordinating bodily functions.

Cultural perception

The perception of electricity has evolved dramatically. In the 19th century, before its widespread adoption, electricity was often viewed with a mixture of awe and apprehension, sometimes depicted as a mysterious, almost magical force capable of extraordinary feats. This fascination was fueled by early experiments like [Luigi Galvani](/Luigi_Galvani)'s work with frog legs, which sparked imaginations and likely inspired tales of reanimation, such as Mary Shelley's [Frankenstein](/Frankenstein).

As electricity became the lifeblood of the [Second Industrial Revolution](/Second_Industrial_Revolution), its portrayal shifted. Figures like the linemen who maintained the electrical infrastructure were increasingly cast as heroes, diligently working with this powerful force. Fictional and real-life "masters of electricity," from [Jules Verne](/Jules_Verne) to [Nikola Tesla](/Nikola_Tesla), were often depicted with near-wizardly abilities.

In the latter half of the 20th century, as electricity became an indispensable necessity, its presence was primarily noted when it failed. Power outages became potent symbols of disaster, while the individuals responsible for maintaining the flow of electricity, like the nameless hero in Jimmy Webb's song "[Wichita Lineman](/Wichita_Lineman)," were often celebrated for their vital, albeit often unseen, contributions.